+ What is a Thread Pool?

    A thread pool is a collection of reusable worker threads that execute submitted tasks.
    Threads are created once and kept ready
    Tasks are submitted to the pool
    An available thread executes the task
    After completion, the thread returns to the pool
    Threads are reused, not recreated

    âœ” Improves performance
    âœ” Saves system resources

+ Thread Pool Working (Based on Example)
    ThreadPoolExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolExecutor(
        2,                // corePoolSize
        4,                // maximumPoolSize
        1, TimeUnit.HOURS,// keepAliveTime
        new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(2),
        new CustomThreadFactory(),
        new CustomRejectHandler()
    );

    corePoolSize
    Minimum number of threads kept alive (even if idle)

    maximumPoolSize
    Maximum number of threads allowed in the pool

    keepAliveTime
    Time extra threads stay alive when idle

    timeUnit
    Unit for keepAliveTime (SECONDS, MINUTES, HOURS)

    workQueue
    Queue that holds waiting tasks when threads are busy

    threadFactory
    Creates threads (name, priority, daemon, etc.)

    handler (RejectedExecutionHandler)
    Action taken when tasks cannot be accepted

    Execution Flow:

    First 2 tasks â†’ handled by core threads
    Next 2 tasks â†’ placed in queue
    Extra tasks â†’ new threads created (up to max = 4)
    If pool + queue full â†’ rejection handler invoked
    Idle extra threads removed after keep-alive time

